[1] Tamil Nadu (Dharmapuri)
Date: Wed 5 Jul 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <a-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Chennai Online, Chennai, India, 5 Jul 2006 [edited]
<<http://www.chennaionline.com/colnews/newsitem.asp?NEWSID=%7B17CBAF09-33CA-4DBD-BF48-6155A196D13E%7D&CATEGORYNAME=Tamil+Nadu>http://www.chennaionline.com/colnews/newsitem.asp?NEWSID=%7B17CBAF09-33CA-4DBD-BF48-6155A196D13E%7D&CATEGORYNAME=Tamil+Nadu>

As many as 1049 persons have been affected by chikungunya (a form of
viral fever) in Dharmapuri district of Tamil Nadu, collector M.
Chandrashekharan said here today [5 Jul 2006].
Talking to reporters, he said 698 persons had been affected in rural
areas and 351 in urban limits. All the 5 government hospitals, 30
primary health centers and private hospitals have been alerted and
special wards arranged in Dharmapuri Government Hospital.
Blood samples have been sent to the Central Virological Laboratory,
Pune and Institute of Vector Control and Zoonosis, Hosur for further
tests.
No casualty [mortality? - Mod.TY] has been reported so far, the collector said.
As many as 1685 committees have been formed to create awareness among
the people of the district by conducting door-to-door verification.
The campaign from 7 to 28 Jul 2006 is expected to cover 14 lakh [1
400 000] people of the district, he added.
--
